<p><span id="internal-source-marker_0.227613982046023">On the steep, inhospitable slopes of the Andes, at altitudes from 1,000 - 4,000 masl, grow a group of nine, extremely nutritious, edible roots and tubers.  The weird and wonderful looking Andean Root and Tuber Crops (ARTC) are found  from southeastern Venezuela to northwest Argentina, with the greatest diversity concentrated in Peru, Bolivia and Ecuador. </span><span></span></p>
<p><span>These hardy, millennial super foods withstand drought, freezing temperatures and UV exposure. They are prized for their medicinal properties, and offer unique potential for the 21st century problems of food security, malnutrition, and climate change. </span><span></span></p>
<p><span>CIP protects and maintains the remarkable genetic diversity of wild and domestic Andean crop species threatened by extinction or genetic weakening. The genebank, contains some 1,500 samples collected from seven countries. </span><span></span></p>
<p><span>Possessing high vitamin, micronutrient, and starch content the health benefits and medicinal properties of ARTC are considerable. At least two are thought to have strong influences on human sexual desire. Link to main uses common name edible part and how it’s used Researchers monitor ARTC’s nutritional properties,</span><span></span></p>
<p><span>Researchers also find ways to increase farmer income in the highlands through their sustainable use and export. </span></p>